Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on the introduction of administrative liability for violation of the terms and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) when purchasing for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve a very acute problem of non-fulfillment of its obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded unfunded contracts, tried in every possible way to evade the obligations to pay and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the prosecutor's office has made 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials were brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 administrative ones were brought to administrative ones, 75 materials were submitted to the investigative bodies for organizing procedural inspections, 46 of them criminal cases were initiated.
As a result, debts to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles were repaid.
Moreover, these huge amounts were accumulated far from as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
To fabulous debts resulted in numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs by much more modest amounts.
Here's a typical case.
The head of a small company won a competition for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The person invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial pile of debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would lead to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur did not seek help from the prosecutor’s office.
Now in a number of regions the problem has been leveled as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor’s office operates in the mode of manual anti-crisis management.
The Prosecutor General personally holds on-site meetings with representatives of local authorities, which deal with all violations revealed by prosecutors and measures for their immediate elimination.
Such operational meetings this year have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of Federal Law No. 189-FZ “On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offenses Regarding the Establishment of Administrative Liability of Officials of the Customer for Violation of the Terms and Procedure for Payment of Goods (Works, Services) in Procurement to Ensure State and Municipal Needs”, which was signed by the President of Russia last week, will be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the practical application of these legislative innovations.
Civil Rights Group Announces Traffic Warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People travel warning, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, guests, and citizens of Missouri to be particularly vigilant and exercise increased caution when traveling around the state in connection with a number of questionable racist incidents recently occurring throughout the state and cited here."
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the move was prompted by a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, and that state law enforcement agencies are disproportionately targeting minorities.
“You have people who are violating human rights.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, they are beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored Missouri, told the Kansas City Star.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of this kind announced by the organization in relation to the state of the United States.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a twenty-eight-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gasoline during a trip to the state, and Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office that found black drivers were 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is to keep people informed and alert their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People should be prepared in one way or another, whether they take money with them for bail or inform relatives that they are traveling around the state.”
According to the FBI’s latest Hate Crimes Reporting Program, there were 100 hate crimes reported in Missouri in 2015, making the state the 16th most hate crimes in the state.
The move warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to bring legal action against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws that required local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, was supposed to increase the number of checks on racial grounds.
Traffic warnings are usually issued by the State Department in relation to other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
