Blocking critics on Facebook: Don’t run for public office unless you’re willing to listen to voter criticism
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism irritated him, of course.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to his critics.
As early as 1783, Washington said, “You can take away the freedom of speech and lead us, deaf and dumb, like sheep to the slaughter.”
I will now turn to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should have tried to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called this lawsuit null and void, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well and that."
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it's important, too.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a Democratic-dominated state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He showed a strong hand in the management of the state and commitment to his principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as a primary way to connect with his constituents and with jokes demonstrates on his page his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's page - which is declared as an official public forum and is conducted by administration employees with taxpayers' money - is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking comments was just their moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters mauling the internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls, a teacher, a businessman, a pastor who turn to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer, Sarma Raman of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the Post.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called cheat, instead of admitting they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life stance.”
In the Facebook era, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is far less dusty work than it used to be when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical editorials, or arresting and shutting down protesters.
But this is exactly what is happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media platforms.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris of Alexandria, the chairman of the Loudon County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending made about the same revolution as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely damaged his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Yurikola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Portius" wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was littered with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, Commerce, and Navigation.
But he didn’t try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means accepting it.
