Poverty and death in Indonesia’s “golden land”
Bardina Degei does not use the stove when preparing her lunch.
She rarely even uses a pot.
In her wooden home in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually just puts the sweet potato, which is called "note", right into the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and eaten by impatient, unwashed hands.
Degeia sits on the ground floor - she has no furniture - and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The bathroom serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men from this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five o’clock,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, raising their hands publicly in front of occupying forces.
The current independence movement from the Netherlands has quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which retains tight control over the region while preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabira, and then a five-hour shake-up on a hired car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians, not to mention journalists, and almost none of the foreigners came here.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degeya says, pointing to her bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
It is also Indonesian gold.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a mountainous province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport produced approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the cost of which is estimated at $ 78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia's powerful armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
Demands for greater autonomy by the Papuans threaten the existence of this gold mine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, since 1969, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, massacres in Papua’s highlands in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” the report, published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture — especially frequent, according to another report, rape and electrocution — and violent suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because accidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts dragged on as Papua's resources attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive.
Javanese shops, "varungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than Papuan natives,” explains Abet You, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of work.
"Because of this, Papua's indigenous people - mother-mother (women) of Papua - have lost their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to tackle inequality and human rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua's 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice,” says You.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi’s October inauguration, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols at a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of the darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Jawedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers, who were drunk, chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Eimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A couple of hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the white, a dance of the Papuan tribe mee pago: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, the soldiers were told by internal radio communication: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” as it sounded, as stated in an official document seen by TIME magazine correspondents, but which was not published in the local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayame, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who shot, but says that the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
A local resident, Alphius Yove, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME magazine.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
Gen. Yotje Mende, a senior Papuan police inspector, told reporters that his officers were only "defending" their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi delivered a passionate speech in Jayapura, in which he expressed condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights abuses.
But they almost immediately made excuses.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or early zeros.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be done,” he said.
Viranto then retracted his remarks, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to establish an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through the court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody East Timor independence vote in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of Paniai received such statements with gloomy distrust.
“I’ve been questioned four times in the last three years, but there’s been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
"I'm tired."
He says he's still living in fear years later.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid I’ll be arrested by the military, I’m afraid I’ll be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came for me,” he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in the neighboring district of Deiyai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take the man unconscious to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of a construction site office owned by the company.
Police said villagers threw stones at officers who responded by firing warning shots.
But local residents claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began to shoot at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retribution,” said Domingue Badia, 29, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being rushed.
“I hid in my house for two days.”
Deiyai’s parliament demanded that the officers involved be called to account and that a mobile police brigade be recalled from the region.
Paniai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes dissatisfaction with the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green areas of the central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to defend the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military in Paniai in recent years under the pretext of “defending national independence”.
Some never came back.
Among Papua's population, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten tubers note cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, there has been an increase in economic inequality between the indigenous Papuans and the new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to the airport of Nabira.
Few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village ... because there’s no work or money here,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
The isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudie and Basil Longshan were deported from Papua for “insufficient coordination with relevant organizations” despite being given rare video permits.
According to Felim Keene, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jokowi’s election campaign to lift restrictions on the work of the media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces of Papua and West Papua are now facing new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is mostly limited to Papua's immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands — asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
A spokesman for Indonesia's Foreign Ministry, Arramanata Nasir, dismissed the group's statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so hiding evidence of human rights abuses would be difficult."
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch human rights ambassador Kiis Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke their silence by saying, “We want freedom,” according to a source who was also present at the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold new presidential elections in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
“Jokowi is a man who has good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribe’s council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat of a greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobai says that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote for Jokovi a debt that he must pay.
“They don’t want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly in front of the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not let the guilty forget about their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says, without raising his head.
“What else were we to do?”
