The head of the EPA Pruitt refuses to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted under Obama to reduce emissions
The day after the lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency canceled his decision to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted under Obama, designed to reduce emissions of substances that pollute the air and lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that now his agency listens more than under previous administrations to the needs of environmental regulators in individual states.
He made no mention of the lawsuit against his previous position filed in the federal appeals court.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline for states to ensure compliance with 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay compliance by one year to give his agency more time to study the plan and avoid "mismatching local decisions or impeding economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma’s attorney general before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or postponed the introduction of norms that the chemical or gas-oil industry opposed.
An unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Puitt to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA exceeded his authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that by dramatically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s responsibility to work with states in a comprehensive process to meet the new standards in a timely manner.
“Under previous administrations, the EPA has often failed to meet deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others, and discussed timelines in the course of resolving the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through litigation, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the power it gives us.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt may at some point again use his "powers for deferral and other statutory powers" to ensure that the rules "jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of the ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay the implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on this issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states filing this week's lawsuit against the EPA, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The change in the course of the EPA — following our lawsuits — is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the smog sweeping their cities,” Schneiderman said.
New York's lawsuit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and Washington, D.C., as well as the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone occurs when conventional pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries and chemical plants and other sources react with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe breathing problems in susceptible people, resulting in thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health and environmental advocates welcomed Pruitt’s sudden change of course.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
