Murder at Morse Ford: Activists Will Lose Lynch Courts on Stage to Call for Justice
The 1948 Ford Mercury passed the audience in the village of Monroe in Georgia and roared to the small bridge of Morse Ford.
When the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked her path.
The main one - a middle-aged man in a suit in a thin strip - pulled a cigar and looked through the windshield.
The people inside were trembling with fear.
"We need that nigger, Roger!" the man grumbled.
"Get him out of the car!"
The shrill screams broke the silence as the young black man was pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene, which took place on July 22, is just a staging.
But when a noose was thrown around Roger's neck, almost all the audience actually held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to replay the night in 1946 when two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and May Murray Dorsey, were lynched by the Cuckoos.
No one has been convicted of these murders.
“It’s amazing that no one has been arrested in all these years — even though we see them around us; even though we know who they are,” says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
"It's a stain on our history and it's a stone on our souls."
Brooks, 71, is a former member of the Georgia Congress who has fought for human rights all his life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to Monroe residents that injustice has never been corrected.
“We want an investigation, we want an end, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
"We can't move on to healing and reconciliation until we get justice."
A coroner covers the body of one of the victims of Morse Ford's lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI records obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
While the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always been well aware of two related lynching motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote in the primaries that were to take place that summer.
At about the same time, according to FBI reports, black enforcer Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, in a fight, apparently because of a woman.
Brooks says Hester was rumored to have slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy, and that the baby she was supposed to have was not from her husband.
According to FBI reports, on July 25, 1946, Loi Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 bail to get Malcolm out of prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of jail and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
“It turns out that he organized and commanded the Harrison murders,” one of the FBI reports concludes.
“It’s also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement that not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses.”
Brooks calls it shorter.
“It was an attack on voting rights,” he said.
"They were all killed to send a message to the blacks in town: If you register and vote, you'll get the same."
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has directed an annual performance reproducing that lynching at the Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is visual, it captures the viewer and tells about the deep racism, which, as many would like to believe, is no longer in America.
It’s hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green believes that’s what matters.
“We don’t want to talk about Lynch courts because they show us our own ugliness,” she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you unless you hear me or hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year's play began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - gathered indoors and listened to a polished review of the play over the years.
Wade Marbo was a director with Greene.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role never became easier.
“I think I got dirty because that’s not the person I am,” Marbo says.
“But I think it’s very important to remember that story because we don’t want to go back to that time.”
In the room, the actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The spectacle begins with Malcolm, enraged that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Raccoon screams in response.
There's a punch.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) burst into laughter.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What is it," Asks Ascona.
He is worried and confused.
Am I overreacting?
"No," Green says through laughter.
"I just don't think white people said 'nigga' back then."
“Yes,” laughed one of the black men.
"You've got to miss the hard 'r'."
And the energy in the room also changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of comradeship.
Everyone should do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four people killed.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona says the word "n", it turns out clear and sharp.
No one is laughing.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by a word.
Within a hundred yards of her, fifty spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
The audience is almost equal in number of blacks and whites.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to watch the performance; many live nearby.
They endured nearly eight hours of Georgia's heavy spirit while Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up to this point, the murders were only history, but now that they are standing in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are immediately in the air.
When the last note of the song subsides, Greene invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children bend over to their heads, touch the paint depicting blood, and still bodies and whisper something to each other.
"They're not really dead," mutters one little boy, as if to remind himself.
A few minutes later, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly everything ends.
Actors drop ropes from their necks and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, the man in the suit who played the main puppeteer.
Nick Rascona hugs two other actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional load of the play finally fell on him.
"It's okay," whispers one of the women.
“We know you have a good heart.
You had a reason for that.”
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta are busy discussing the performance with the black couple they just met.
Denise Duplinski finds it hard to find words to describe how she feels after the performance.
“It’s hard to listen to those horrible, creepy words and actions... people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,” she says.
“After that, I think lynchings are still happening,” she adds, “only now is it called what the police are shooting at.”
In another corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks, who remembers his work as a human rights activist at mealtimes, grabbed everyone’s attention.
He says he’s already started planning next year’s show.
“The production inspires us because it not only describes the horror of what we have experienced, but also teaches us,” he says.
"Because if you don't learn from this lesson, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.
