Good-natured Coop (Showalter), now a writer, still hasn't achieved reciprocity from Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) has not yet parted with his virginity.
And then there is the crazy and vile conspiracy in which Ronald Reagan (also Showalter) is involved, who is now instigated by George Bush Sr. (a tested parody performed by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is getting away from it.
It is especially funny to see forever young Rudd, who sings the song of Matt Dillon from “Lonely”, whose character, the former big man Andy looks now an old man.
To bring this franchise success could be random madness in the spirit of the recursive series “Seven Up”, until it reaches what, in my opinion, would be its logical conclusion: “Hot American Summer: twenty years later”, where in the last scene the whole company would go to the cinema for the premiere of the film “Hot American Summer”.
“Comrade Detective” on Amazon refers to another type of nostalgia: memories of the Cold War from “Americans”, “Explosive Blonde” or even “Shine” with its images of the struggle between East and West.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka with director Reese Thomas, portrays a TV movie: an 80s Romanian police drama about two police officers in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism, and the Marxist-Leninist path.
The main roles - who saw the life of Gregor and the idealist Joseph - are played by Florin Piersik Jr. and Corneliu Street, and their dialogues in English were voiced by Channing Tatum (also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
That's a brilliant idea.
But only an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (police officers spend time watching a chess match as Americans might watch football).
The team of famous voices behind the scenes - among them Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - allows you to play an interesting game of "guess the voice".
But "Comrade Detective" so clings to the plausibility of clumsy propaganda drama - there is even a killer in the mask of Ronald Reagan - which often looks like it.
Six long episodes are long, and it's not funny very often.
If it had been shorter, Comrade Detective might have handled his agitprop satire better; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph come to the American embassy, two fat men are sitting in the lobby devouring a bunch of hamburgers.
