The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to later announce that interest rates will not change after weak economic growth and weakening inflation dampened rumors of a possible rise.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain sluggish and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on family incomes.
The Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 in favor of keeping rates at 0.25%, with fewer committee members in favor of rate hikes this month because weak economic growth weakened support for the hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank limited its forecasts to a 1.7% rise in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on family incomes will continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to about 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes over the next few years would be needed to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said borrowing costs would likely have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
Also, the members of the Committee voted to abandon part of the huge package of measures for the development of the economy, launched a year ago due to Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close its emergency financing plan, under which it provides banks with cheap loans, although it said that it now has to provide another 15 billion pounds under this plan - up to 115 billion pounds.
In the rate decision protocol, the bank said: “According to MPC’s main projections, gross domestic product (GDP) growth is going to remain slow in the near term, while pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption.”
On the issue of rates, he reiterated that to halt inflation would require “some tightening of fiscal policy,” at a “slightly higher” rate than markets expect.
At the moment, the markets predict the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another one in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all the increases will be “gradual” and “limited”.
The bank’s forecasts for this year and next are lower than the forecasts made in May, which were equal to 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank left unchanged its forecast for 1.8% in 2018.
Following this news, sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change the rate was made after recent disappointing growth figures weakened the increased expectation of an increase; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the representative of the bank, growth, apparently, will remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will begin to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The bank’s latest inflation report gave little cause for joy to households hit by high inflation and very minor wage hikes: according to the bank, the pressure will intensify before declining.
The bank added that financial policy “cannot prevent” a payday in the next few years, but expects wages to “significantly” recover by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of the growing demand for British goods, due to the low exchange rate of the pound, which compensates for some of the reduced consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were cut to 0.25 percent last August after the shock results of a referendum on leaving the European Union caused the pound to fall.
The bank estimates it will likely take four years to fully impact prices and the economy.
Before the bank made its latest rate decision, there was growing noise around the expected rate hikes as inflation weighed more and more on already pressured households: three committee members asked for rates to be raised to 0.5% in July.
Last month, inflation fell to 2.6% from 2.9% in July, although, according to the bank, this drop was expected and will be compensated again in the coming months.
