Beginning in September, patients will have access to a “revolutionary” HIV-prevention drug after a battle in the High Court over funding for the drug from the Public Health Service.
The NHS has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (pre-exposure prophylaxis), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in those at risk by an average of 86 per cent, will now be provided by the health service for an initial three-year trial period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to fund the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that argued the National Health Service had the ability to pay for PrEP despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was described as a "major innovation" by National Health Service President Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Authority (NAT) called it a "turning point".
Before the full launch of the program across England by April 2018, venereological dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start registering people, and even more dispensaries will join the program in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PREP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex in the human body, a sufficient number of certain drugs to prevent infection with HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
Dispensaries will select suitable participants who agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people and persons whose partners are not aware of whether their HIV status is constrained by antiretroviral therapy.
People living with and assigned to a GP in England will also be able to apply for a potential participation in the nearest venereological dispensary taking part in the program.
The program will cost ?10 million, and the National Health Service of England signed a contract to provide the drug this week after an international procurement tender.
The study is designed to assess all the possibilities of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, its digestibility and application on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and reinforce the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the biggest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT, said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly aimed at people in need and at risk, provides an opportunity to change the situation with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV will have access to a new, empowering tool in England that they can control without talking to a partner, leading to many more lives.
We warmly welcome this news.”
Ian Greene, president of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “The first thing to do now is to ensure that the test is quickly rolled out across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is forgotten.
Now that we have the experimental drug PrEP, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk for HIV.”
Shadow Minister of Public Health Sharon Hodgson said: “We very much welcome the start of the trial of PrEP, it is very late due to months of delays and procrastination on the part of the government.”
The data demonstrate how revolutionary this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping transmission of this fatal infection.
This test will bring us a step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the trial be deployed nationwide as soon as possible to protect those at risk of HIV and take us a step further towards ending the spread of HIV in society.
