Judges are asked to protect from the presidents
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and introduce their election.
For courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court must also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out by the HRC on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with members of the council.
At a meeting with members of the council on December 8, 2016, certain cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens were discussed (see "Kommersant" of December 9).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights activists is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of other judges.
If a candidate for the post of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, then the president of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, must submit him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to allocate cases to judges.
To do this, experts admit, can a specially written computer program.
Also in the HRC believe that the Chairman is not entitled to “determine the results of the qualification certification of the judge, initiate his disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to proceed to the “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “entrust them with powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation.”
Now all presidents of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize an appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take the practice of arbitration courts as a basis.
There are “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use the “telephone right”.
The HRC proposes to strengthen the justices of the peace with the participation of people’s assessors to consider some “categories of civil and administrative cases”.
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, the restoration of work, the protection of honor and dignity, the deprivation of a driver's license, etc.
"These are just our proposals," said HRC member, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morshchakova.
She also recalled that the order of the President applied not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the execution of the order from the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev should until September 1.
Live a high life: half-floor and cunning design techniques turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a nice model house in the style of Queen Anne, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not collect her belongings and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.”
Since the first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment underwent a complete renovation.
Initially, it was a one bedroom apartment with a complex layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a semi-floor to squeeze the maximum benefit from the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi from the Notting Hill-based architectural design studio Duck & Shed to use 12.5 feet high ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but suitable for Joan to live in.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural challenge was to create a semi-floor where you could stand full-length.
Erfan had to think creatively to handle the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We needed to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not only to build a simple platform, but also to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the premises from above and below. ”
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in the allotted space - and many more interesting things.
From the half-story through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" offers a view of the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with a golden finish, silver accents and vintage lighting devices from Serge Mui set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding entertainment, space and light.
A short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it seem longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored protective panel seems to be a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets serve to store all of Joan's dishes.
To create a feeling of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can block the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the kitchen.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding up door, as in a garage.
“Engineering art was involved here,” Erfan says of the steel-reinforced fiberboard door.
“It’s fitted with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“At the end of the day, floor space is exactly what you’re going to sell, which is what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will enter and make calculations based on the area of the sexes.”
Here they were able to increase the floor area using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection to the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This serves as evidence that due to good design and increased footage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
