On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
“The decision on our case will be made soon by the court,” Colin wrote.
The new chief of staff trump plans to limit the flow of information to the President.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media, hoping to keep the chief in a calmer state.
Here's what reporter Josh Dawesy says.
“At a meeting held by the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, with the leadership of the White House on his first working day, he outlined the main problem in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to solve: poor channels of information to the president.”
Kelly told employees that information should go through him — paper or through briefings — because the president would be better placed to make decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly’s diagnosis is completely correct, but others have already failed, trying to pacify Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump’s relationship with television dates back decades — and now that he’s in the White House, his TV habit is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, resented unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to demonstrate to him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be persuaded,” Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico that “in the words of six former campaign members, in order to keep under control Trump’s habit of tweeting, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information coming to him personally.”
Okay.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habit was ever “under control” is simply ridiculous.
Maybe those campaign members know something we don’t — for example, that if it weren’t for them, Trump’s tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about tweets that Trump has not posted.
If his employees saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has ever been able to keep Trump from adding fuel to the fire.
Part of the problem is that in a White House divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by giving Trump material — reliable or not — that validates their views.
"Politico" - just to this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly give the president dubious information.
Here is one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
Trump’s current and former employees say Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened in late February, when someone slipped the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsh was accused of “standing for a number of leaks” in the White House.
It does not matter that Johnson is forever banned from Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he did not present specific facts or that in the past he launched false accusations and then abandoned them.
Trump read the article and started asking employees about Welsh.
Goldmacher adds that the then chief of staff, Reince Priebus, and the secretary of staff, Rob Porter, “tried to build a system to manage the flow of papers that Trump receives and document them.”
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump still has an impulsive nature, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly’s task very difficult.
The Tyumen Prosecutor’s Office is fighting against HIV-dissident
The prosecutor's office challenged the decision of the Kalinin district court of Tyumen, which stopped the criminal case against a local resident, whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor's office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to create a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection 4B stage.
According to prosecutors, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
“The woman was not treated herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist,” explained the Prosecutor’s office of the Tyumen region.
The criminal case went to the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that “forgive his wife, has no complaints about her, she made amends and apologized.”
The prosecutor's office did not agree with the court's decision and appealed, demanding to cancel the order to dismiss the case and send it for a new consideration.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the damage caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection," the press service of the prosecutor's office said.
In the opinion of the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise other HIV-dissidents will follow her example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care because of the refusal of parents.
"And this situation has already improved - for a year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV changed their opinion - they allowed to diagnose, began to take drugs," Elena Loseva, a spokeswoman for the AIDS Center, said.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be found - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
What are the risks of HIV-dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first in Russia study of the so-called movement of HIV-dissidents.
HIV-dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and see their spread as a serious threat.
