“In Libya, we don’t want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict.”
The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations of opposing Libyan parties have frequented visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on intra-Libyan settlement at the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told Kommersant what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it relies.
Almost nothing is known about the contact group on Libya that you are leading.
Let's say the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was established at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Foreign Minister Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya. - "Kommersant").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mechanic Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Kommersant").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists and representatives of the State Duma was created, and our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you manage to lead it?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been approached to lead the group’s work.
Our activities were not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanics.
We managed to establish contacts with representatives of all the main groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both on the part of Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Saraj is based. - "Kommersant"), and with Tobruk (the residence of the parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. - "Kommersant").
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Kommersant"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, and dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with any of the parties to the conflict, we are conducting a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are currently five people in the contact group.
Among them are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include representatives of the Middle East Institute of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the group of specialists in the region.
No one from our staff is permanently in Libya, there is no need for this yet.
Are there Russian military advisers and instructors in Libya now?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All conversations and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities closed to us until a certain point, like Misrata (where militias are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years).
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that there are all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there, analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the units that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the Islamic State banned in Russia - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, to meet these people, to verify that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion did you reach?
Has the Islamic State defeated Haftar in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from April 19 to April 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Rosgvardia.
You, as we understood, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the mood of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements, the elections reached at the end of July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, will the agreements be broken, the fighting resume, the parties will try to seize power single-handedly?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Saraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
It is often written and said that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on this very day.
It was a coincidence.
But in Misrata they did not believe in coincidence.
We were told: “You must be very brave people who came to us today.”
But our task is to show that we do not support only Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key parties to the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar talked.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR make mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level easier?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
If he knows Russian, it is very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us, of course, facilitates a dialogue with him.
And by the way, not just with him.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or still in the Soviet Union.
And here they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you think it is likely that the arms embargo imposed on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, the Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
The process of drafting a constitution is currently under way in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions and achieve internal consensus.
Then the elections should take place, as was discussed at the meeting between Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and the legitimate government is finally elected (and now none of the parties has such a status), then you can raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by allies from the EU.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar’s troops would take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers ferrying immigrants to Europe?
Very timely question.
We are actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, Saraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And tribes in southern Libya play a big role in this issue, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about stopping the flow of migrants at a distance?
That is, conditionally speaking, turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants go?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the southerners in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first we would like to see the unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist who supports the introduction of Sharia law in the country.
How radical are his views?
Will this not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
Islamists are in the coalition.
Yes, but he himself adheres to the position that Libya should be a completely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting terrorists.
Why does he have such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where there is legislative, executive and judicial power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not getting in there.
And we mixed all the cards and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded an agreement on cooperation with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft head Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess to resell.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
There are plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
In particular, we are talking about previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, we are talking, as in the case of Iran, about the “oil for services” scheme?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not directly deal with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya and not the main thing.
In fact, we are doing peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to agree among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and to squeeze out terrorists from there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that today not a single person from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said he had about 50,000 phone records of Islamist and radical groups and did not speak Russian.
Which countries are these fighters from?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Then let’s formulate the question differently.
How many Libyans are among the Islamist militants in Libya?
There are practically no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are aliens.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
There are still several visits to take place, and then hopefully there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
