The Hubble telescope captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature causes water in the planet's atmosphere to glow in the infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to the so-called "hot Jupiters" - gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the Solar system, but located ten times closer to the parent star.
Because of this, a year on an exoplanet lasts only 1.3 “earthly” days, and its gas shell is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change is threatening lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and southern France, but now there are concerns that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender has become worse due to dry weather and insect-carrying diseases; this has caused a constant headache for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Sches, an expert from the Provence-based agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: “The lavand in Provence is really under threat because in recent years this plant has been feeling the effects of climate change: there has been much less rain in the spring and especially in the fall.
This affects the life span of lavender.
And there are also small cicadas that jump on the leaves of insects that carry micro-bacteria; in very dry weather, they become very much. ”
A lot is at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very popular in perfumery and cosmetology.
Eric Sches says: "Instead of very long ears with a large number of large colors, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or absent.
So we have fewer parts that contain essential oil.”
Solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding varieties more drought-resistant.
