The murder of a journalist underscores the growing danger in Mexico.
Employees of the weekly newspaper “Riodose” usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in the state of Sinaloa related to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war drug traffickers.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told to change their habits.
Two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to an office where a grenade had already been thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - proof is not needed, suspicion and internal sensations will be enough.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held by the government or the cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence is not giving a break, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year, at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter - their publisher and inspirer, co-founder of "Riodose" Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very keenly, although his presence is everywhere - a large photograph of Valdez showing his middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the Riodos building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that depict his smile, face with glasses or his trademark Panama.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their general trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, only two cases have been investigated so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders each year involving drug trafficking and organized crime, journalists’ killers are rarely brought to justice.
Riodos journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although it is now much more dangerous around.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings is of little use, - says Ibarra.
"It's very silly to waste time in this seminar," he says.
"Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the Riodos office in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the newspaper's name - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove off in his car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly across Culiacan.
But about Valdez almost everything is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the United States last January, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Not to mention the fact that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug kings, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of “calm” is just when one of the cartels takes control of the coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodos, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is at war with the sons of Guzman.
The publication could anger the sons; people who were allegedly members of the gang bought up all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper was seized, which wrote about the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be there.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroest and in 2003, together with five colleagues, founded Riodos, selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to engage in journalism without touching on the subject of drugs," Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this edition they could read about what no one else dared to write.
Eight years after its founding, Riodos won the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for Reporting in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating the drug trade in Mexico, wherever it led.
He admitted frankly that he was scared.
"I want to live on," he said at the CPJ Awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is “a way of life,” he said in an October interview with Rompeviento TV.
"You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist - either that or you're just fooling around."
I don't want to be asked, "What were you doing when there were so many deaths...why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
Riodos employees miss Valdez, a joker who swore like a port loader, a friend generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to moan alive.
They relied on the order they set up.
He always had to wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar in front of the office, and always sit at the same table there.
Now they ask: has his love for the once-established order ruined him?
His death made them question their calculations on how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you get to know their wives, their children, their legal businesses, and their underground drug trafficking airfields.
"These things were beyond the line," Bohorkes said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and a desire for self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from anything that smells bad.
The problem, says Riodos editor Andrés Villareal, is that "smell can be fooled... and then what happened to Javier happens."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa — as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states where there is a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where the employees of “Riodose” gathered for a security training, suddenly it was forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days before it became known that spyware that are sold exclusively to governments are used in Mexico to spy on journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers take refuge in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were instructed by the state government to guard the office of Riodos, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these police officers were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officials about whom the governor himself said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue of "Riodos" counted on three main topics.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chavez.
They also had an exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor's hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the D.A.'s office.
It was not officially announced who had been kidnapped or how it happened, so caution had to be exercised when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was the favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which dominated all levels of government for almost the past century.
Recently, several PRI governors have faced high-profile corruption charges.
Villareal asked reporters to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzman’s son El Chapo escaped a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have looked for Valdez's column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
“We would have known what had happened before,” says Villareal, 46, who is nicknamed “El Flaco” because of his thin physique.
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources have been severed."
Valdez’s office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killing of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took some posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor’s office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the state of Michoacan in the west of the country three days after Valdez was killed.
Found the burned body, and the authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak out, organize protests and write “SOS Press” on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington, D.C., seeking international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with Governor Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their murders for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her more assignments to cover the government’s activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its complicity in government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, “Drug Journalism,” he wrote that reporters are not just being killed by gangs of drug traffickers; they are doing so on the orders of politicians and security services colluding with organized crime.
The Articulo 19 Press Protection Committee estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were ordered by police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez says.
Of course, killing scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Masias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note was found on her body, allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I'm here because of my articles."
A computer keyboard and headphones were lying next to her severed head.
Some publications chose to close as El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Brich was murdered in March.
Others continue to hold on like Nuevo Laredo’s El Maniana after its leader’s assassination in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly reached out to drug cartels with a front-page editorial entitled "What Do You Want From Us?"
Some journalists have left their home states or even the country.
It's a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they are still looking for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work daily balance between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is afraid to write about the drug trade.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready for publication, the publishers of Riodos were sitting on the sidewalk near the office and drinking beer, when suddenly their phones simultaneously rang.
A series of skirmishes between rival gangs and security forces near the resort town of Masatlan left behind, according to confirmed data, 19 corpses.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from the cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted news on the Riodos website via their mobile phone.
The next day, the first page had to be redesigned.
There were sirens nearby - another firefight in the vicinity.
Bochorkes looked at whether the police officers guarding them were ready for defense.
If they were scared, they didn’t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was put on display throughout Sinaloa, the employees of Riodos continued his work.
"How can you think of closing down," said Bohorquez, "if on the very day Javier was killed, the trainee asked me to send her outside to report?"
Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit terrifying.
The researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros, discovered by a Canadian miner, preserved so well that experts called it “Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
It is so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown — and to say that he had, in some ways, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as "the best preserved of the Tireophores in the history of the finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
His incredible good condition stunned researchers, who call him “really remarkable.”
This herbivore thyrophore is the best preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
He was found by Sean Funk while he was working at Sancor's Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He stumbled upon something that seemed different from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was underway to detect an animal inside an earth block weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work has been done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
"It's only worth squinting a little bit, and you can almost believe that he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, where the creation is shown.
“It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs — the Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.”
Studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, despite the fact that it was covered with shell and resembled a walking tank, apparently, was exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This heavily shelled dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals of our day.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with the environment and avoid meeting enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaur family, was widely reported in print in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum laboratory technician Mark Mitchell, one of the group members who spent more than 7,000 hours behind its painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international group of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and shell plates on his body.
They found a protective coloring, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, meaning that the creature's top was darker than its underside.
Although protective coloration is common, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of living animals with protective coloration.
We can assume that this dinosaur was hunted so actively carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with protective coloration - for example, deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and are more affordable prey, which indicates that the nodosaur had to seriously fight for survival.
“A serious predator threat to a massive, heavily shelled dinosaur shows just how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaurs were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin must have been reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried into the sea, where it sank and lay down on the ocean floor with its back down.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they are now.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, a thyrophore could be hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include the acrocantosaurus, a monster 38 feet (11.5 meters) long, weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to sea after death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum staff, it is the best preserved tireophore in the world, along with skin and shell, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the femur.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous tireophore set a heavy foot on what is now Canada, until a spilled river carried it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell with accuracy to the smallest details.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is “rare as winning the lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more amazing he seems.
Fossilized skin remains still cover the bumpy shell plates dotting the animal's skull.
His right front leg is stretched out along the side, five fingers on it are turned up.
I can count the scales on his sole."
