How did one activist find out the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, browsing the Facebook feed on her phone.
She ran into someone from high school.
It read: “Police officers just killed an 18-year-old child and he’s still lying in the middle of the street.”
Noting that no one else from her tape posted this information, puzzled, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
There were a lot of user reposts with the nickname ?TheePharoah.
A rapper from Greater St. Louis tweeted the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black eighteen-year-old murdered by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's lifeless body spread out in the middle of the street, where it would be for four hours.
"It's wild," thought Ferrell.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put her phone down, and later in the evening returned to tweets that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown's father holding a poster saying, "Ferguson cop just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman pulled the trigger and yelled, “I’m going to kill you all... animals!”
“It’s a non-standard situation,” Ferrel said, according to her own memoirs.
“It’s not a murder like the ones we’re used to and can call typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.”
She took a ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she took her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson in the next almost three years was the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
This is a story about survival and protest, about love and loss, strength and resilience in terms of people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrel was traveling to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a wreath under color, they recalled a conversation that had been conducted countless times before this morning, "about the experience of blacks and their situation."
She recalls saying, “Remember when I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We're going to Ferguson right now because a policeman killed an eighteen-year-old boy and it was wrong."
"I couldn't help but take her," Ferrell later said.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what has happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it and grow up on it.
It must not only be well-versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their position and what we must do to become free in order to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do her a disservice if I shielded her from it."
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists waited for reports of the final non-accusation of Officer Darren Wilson.
There, Ferrell and her daughter joined a local entrepreneur who was preparing lunch packages.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little in his mind, Ferrell took on the form of a new type of activism.
“My activism completely changed after August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Nursing Students, a national minority, and worked on food justice and health inequalities among black communities.
“I don’t have the experience of an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her main cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often white, who came to the community to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His involvement sparked sympathy for the project from Ferrell and six other locals with whom the Whose Streets Project team had been in touch for years after Brown's murder.
“In this documentary, it’s not someone speaking for us or with us, it’s us,” Davis said.
“It was the most important thing for me how these people will be represented, because that’s how I will be represented.”
Although the project’s goal was not to focus on the Ferrel experience at all — in an effort to show that the movement “is not about the rescue leader, but about how the community is united,” as Folayan said — it turned out to be the most open of the participants in the film.
As a result, Whose Streets? shows an unexpectedly personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” said Ferrell, laughingly talking about the first time I saw the finished product.
“But I understood that when you do that kind of work and you humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell's story again discusses and highlights the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the "Black Lives Matter" movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - those who created the tag "BlackLivesMatter" on social networks after the murder of a black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 - identify themselves as homosexuals.
“Black homosexual women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” says Ferrell. “And all because we are constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black homosexual women have to bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed with this statement, noting that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of homosexual black women."
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination", and that Ferrell was not chosen as the film's central character due to her distinctive features.
“She was the person who awakened that energy,” she said.
“On the other hand, it’s not a coincidence that she was in the foreground, because when”
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Ferguson, meanwhile, has long been out of film cameras, but there remain complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking the highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place that she calls home, simply: “The mess.”
She still holds on to the speech she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson full three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
