The emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York, the faces of people hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all somewhat elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Leavenworth prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called “The Emergence of Similarity”.
This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted the sentence just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing Manning’s DNA with a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that people with such a genome might have, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, though not easy-to-understand, manifesto dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data — the different ways in which they are interpreted and the inferential determinism of these interpretations — but also to the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward but has been openly claiming to be a woman since her teens, was sentenced to 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her pictures in prison were not available, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, in which Manning in a platinum tint of a wig, clearly feeling awkward, sits behind the wheel of a car; with this photo she began to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers with great success.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, isolating DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people could look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some kind of portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of the new press exhibition.
Chelsea could not be visited and photographed at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, "Depressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president will soften Chelsea's punishment and she will be able to visit the exhibition in person.
Obama’s decision to release Manning just days after the book was released came as a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There is something profound and powerful about the fact that the exhibition opens right now, when Donald Trump is declaring war on people revealing classified information in the government, and inventing new ways to incite hatred on Twitter, which he is called upon to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the timing of this, she said, "There's no accident."
In a statement written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot above the "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture."
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of penciled C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist puts it in a scientific way), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome doesn’t define what we are, how open genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is,” Dewey-Harborg said in her 2007 video “False Memories.”
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exhibition, mastered in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in the comics.
On it, King Kong-style Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
"So never shut up."
“This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote me,” says the artist, who welcomes us from Philadelphia.
"I still get chills when I talk about it."
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person - as it was presciently depicted in the comics - but when she comes, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic sims, gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, as everyone at the exhibition up to the height (5", Manning's height), on which the pencil was drawn genetic haplogroups.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
"I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, as a movement that stood behind her release as well."
