Startups that will help your company not to become another “Uber”
Aimee Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among the employees of her startup in the field of electronic commerce, but the polls did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He was never consistent or objective,” said Errett, who runs a 75-person company based in San Francisco called Madison Reed, an e-commerce company focused on hair care.
So she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of working with staff, which help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to make express surveys, reach out to certain teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases, allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact the directorate directly.
“Now we have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she had gained a greater understanding of what her employees thought and felt over her three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a thermal map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies gradually realize that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another “Uber”, which was involved in the scandal when a former employee published a blog post in which he described the aggressive environment in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to estimates of the online portal “Let’s talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global management, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than $ 118.7 billion.
Convercent, a Denver, Colorado-based startup that helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid Uber’s declining reputation.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made employee opinion surveys, collect confidential real-time responses, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages, which allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if a top manager is affected, complaints go directly to the management.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that a company mistreats employees or behaves unethically, even if inspectors don’t intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows, and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and to offer an easy way to reach out to the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to search for a phone number or head office email, file a formal complaint, and hope to be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, the head of Ruby Tuesday’s legal department, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, problems that used to be hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay — can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can get closer to a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the employees’ situation,” said Vitrano, who leads the network’s risk management group Ruby Tuesday.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take employee ethics, values and engagement more seriously in 2002, after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Affair.
But it wasn’t until “social media became widespread” that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty underwear from spreading virally online.
“Before we started using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee to use their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors, who supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the total capital of the company to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture, and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they did before.
In highly competitive markets, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just a necessary minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work for a company, feel heard, and that the work they are doing is delivering results, they’re more trying to make that company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors earn income when businesses in their portfolio are doing well; businesses are doing well when employees are committed and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on the involvement of employees.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if change doesn’t come quickly enough, or doesn’t come at all, frustration can develop and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, employees will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why shouldn't I care?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day that someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high staff turnover.
“If you’re not trying to create a culture of transparency, you’re going to lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
