Andrey Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known to "Kommersant", the technical director of the Vostochny Cosmodrome Andrei Okhlopkov began work in the Khrunichev State Space Research and Production Center (SCNPC).
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the leadership of the Center for the Exploitation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (CENKI), he was transferred to an enterprise in the Moscow Branches, where he will coordinate production.
There will be no replacement for Mr. Okhlopkov: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and the functionality will be scattered to the divisions of CENKI.
The fact that the technical director of the East and the deputy general director of CENKI for technological development Andrei Okhlopkov went to work in the Khrunichev SCNPC, "Kommersant" told top managers of several enterprises of the space industry, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
“He has been working at the new post for several weeks,” the interlocutors of “Kommersant” in the industry specified.
It was not possible to get an operational comment from CENKI on Thursday, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was not available for comments.
However, the information "Kommersant" was officially confirmed in the SCNPC.
He decided to move to the position of Director of production coordination, - said the company. - Andrey Okhlopkov assigned to him the task of ensuring the launch minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny Cosmodrome fully completed.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work at CENKI in 2013, having served in the space forces, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome, he held the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, with his filing, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean the separated parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The responsibilities for technological development assigned to him at CENKI were extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a spaceport in the Far East.
Oleg Ostapenko, then head of the Federal Space Agency, said in an interview with Kommersant that the situation in the East "was critical already in October 2013."
The fact is that a strategic mistake was made during the planning: the completion of construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch before the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the terms were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to go on a trick: CENKI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment at unfinished facilities.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and still the transfer occurred (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, says the Kommersant source at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would still not have carried out a single launch from the East, but would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the spaceport, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his “space Susanin”, but it was he who almost always asked for information about the progress of construction.
Mr. Okhlopkov also remembered the directness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the only performer in the East and work directly with subcontractors: "Why should we put all the eggs in one basket of Spetsstroy?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, CENKI has assumed the responsibilities of a general contractor in order to complete construction and installation work on the start-up and technical complex by the planned launches in the fourth quarter.
According to "Kommersant", the reason for the transition of Mr. Okhlopkov to a new place of work were disagreements with the leadership of CENKI regarding the ways of completing the construction of facilities and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of working with subcontractors.
