Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: A diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestines make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not enter the body.
Cells that can trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed towards inflammation, this can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestine appear to increase cell tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan — one of the building blocks of protein — to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that increase tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice were fed, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could promote a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, while the other group, which belonged to the same line but was kept separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice — the communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice's gut cells was sequenced, and six species of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that did not have them.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of fluid — without bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have become tolerance-enhancing cells.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in mice, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when tryptophan levels were reduced by half, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but people suffering from inflammatory bowel disease have been found to have defects in the genes associated with tryptophan.
She says: "Perhaps we need to strengthen the development of these cells, since inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri can potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
