National Union of unskilled, municipal and boiler workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment at the factory McVitie's in Glasgow
The union is seeking assurances from biscuit maker McVitie's managers over its long-term production commitment at the Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company has been silent about the issue of future investment in the Tolkros facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, owner of McVitie’s, said it has invested more than ?5 million in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the work of the facility, employees and representatives of the trade union “will learn about them first.”
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded from McVitie's reaction to the concern that funding would not be used to modernize production lines.
Senior organiser Drew Duffy said: “Members of our union are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the CEO of the facility on business needs and the investment plan for the future of Tolcross.
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is high in local society and in the Greater Glasgow area; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
So, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living wage and chronic decline in production, East End Glasgow desperately needs the prosperity of production at McVitie's factory.
According to Pladis, “The head of the Tolkros facility only yesterday received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our constant cooperation with employees and trade union representatives.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with employees and representatives of the GMB in Tolcross, where we openly discussed a number of issues.
We talked to employees about the fact that like all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions - and this applies to all our facilities and activities - in order to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than 5 million pounds in our Tolkros facility, especially in production lines and improving functional performance.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in the event of any changes in work at this facility, employees and union representatives will be the first to know about it.”
